post_text: With less than a month remaining, Oklahoma ranks 40th nationally for participation in the 2020 Census. For every uncounted resident, an estimated $17,000 in funding is lost each decade. For a family of four, that's a staggering loss of $68,000, much of it federal education funding that our kids so desperately rely on.

post_text:
Dear Drumright Parents/Guardians,
We are very excited to share with our families that the United States Department of Agriculture (USDA) has signed a wavier nationwide that will provide all students meals at no charge from now until the end of December 2020, or until funds for this program are depleted.
Therefore, this means all students in both buildings will be able to eat breakfast and lunch free of charge. It also means virtual students may also have access to these meals at no charge. Starting September 9th virtual students will be able to pick up a grab and go meal at the south side of the Cooper cafeteria at the red kitchen double doors between 12:30 and 1:00. The doors will beâ€¦ More

post_text: We received a report of a possible student exposure to COVID-19. After investigation and discussion with the Creek County Health Dept, it has been determined that no exposure was made at the school facilities or to any students. As a precaution, we will not have anything the rest of this week to allow for disinfecting of the facilities. We are safe to resume Monday, July 6, 2020. This includes Summer Pride workouts at weight room, open gym time and the Softball meeting that was scheduled for Thursday, July 2.

If your student was in the 10th grade during the 2019-20 school year and you anticipate that your 2020 income may be under the $55,000 application limit for the Oklahomaâ€™s Promise scholarship due to recent reductions in your income, you may submit an application based on your 2020 estimated income.

The application must be submitted prior to the June 30, 2020 deadline at: https://secure.okcollegestart.org/applications/Oklahoma_Promise/apply.html. You will be required to provide a copy of your 2020 federal tax return when completed to verify that your 2020 income was under $55,000. The application will be held as pending until the tax documentation is received. Please send any questions to okpromise@osrhe.edu

Oklahomaâ€™s Promise: ALERT for 10th-Grade Parents with Recent Income Loss

https://www.okhighered.org/okpromise/

If your student is or was in the 10th grade during the 2019-20 school year and you anticipate that your 2020 income may be under the $55,000 application limit for the Oklahomaâ€™s Promise scholarship due to recent reductions in your income, you may submit an application based on your 2020 estimated income. The application must be submitted prior to the June 30, 2020 deadline at https://secure.okcollegestart.org/applications/Oklahoma_Promise/apply.html?application_id=3544. You will be required to provide a copy of your 2020 federal tax return when completed to verify that your 2020 income was under $55,000. The application will be held as pending until the tax documentation is received. Please send any questions to okpromise@osrhe.edu.

post_text: PK enrollment for the 2020-2021 school year will be held at Bradley on May 12th from 8:30 AM ti 2:00 PM. We will be practicing social distancing. Once you have received your packet we will direct you to a table by yourself or you may take the paperwork back to your car to fill out. Please bring current shot record, birth certificate, proof of residency. Due to many government offices being closed we will enroll students with a hospital birth certificate. You will be required to present a state birth certificate by Aug. 4th as well as up to date shot records. Please spread the word about this event. We usually fill up very fast.

Secondary Students and Parents:
To begin planning your student's schedule for the 2020-2021 school year, elective choices must be submitted to me by Wednesday, May 6, 2020. If you have questions, please email me at tschuelein@drumright.k12.ok.us. You are welcome to send a phone number for me to call you if needed.

post_text: PK enrollment for the 2020-2021 school year will be held at Bradley on May 12th from 8:30 AM ti 2:00 PM. We will be practicing social distancing. Once you have received your packet we will direct you to a table by yourself or you may take the paperwork back to your car to fill out. Please bring current shot record, birth certificate, proof of residency. Due to many government offices being closed we will enroll students with a hospital birth certificate. You will be required to present a state birth certificate by Aug. 4th as well as up to date shot records. Please spread the word about this event. We usually fill up very fast.

April 22, 2020 marks the 50th anniversary of Earth Day. Earth Day was started 50 years ago to help make a positive change for our planet. The first event had 10% of the U.S. population taking action, People of all ages took to the streets in their communities to clean up. This is the world's largest to date civic event each year.
Facts about Litter in Oklahoma
ODOT spends 4 million taxpayer dollars a year to clean up trash
It costs about $63 a mile to clean trash off of areas around highways
55% of littering occurs along rural and urban highways
60% of litter on the roadway is deliberate.
What can we do? How can we help?
I challenge each student, parent, guardian to get out onâ€¦ More

While the course grade will not be included in the calculation of the core curriculum GPA, the course will count toward the required units for the core curriculum as appropriate. So please share with your friends and tell them to join in and ask questions!!!

post_text: The Oklahoma State School Board will meet in an emergency session today at 4:00 to discuss closing schools across the state. Drumright Public Schools will continue to monitor the news and meet with state officials to determine our best course of action to move forward during this crisis. If schools close, we will meet with staff to implement plans to educate our students remotely. We will review and implement options to provide food services to our students as well. We will keep you informed as the situation progresses.

Drumright Public Schools will have early release tomorrow to allow the faculty to have professional development until 3:45.

School will release at 2:00 at Bradley Elementary and 2:10 at Cooper Middle and Drumright High School.

Busses will transport students home at that time. Varsity athletes in season will remain at school in a study hall and practice will begin after the teachers meeting. Parents should plan to pick up students and students that drive or walk home will be released.

Thank you for supporting Drumright Public Schools!

Kevin Anthony
October 12, 2019 at 9:44 AM Â·

I know there is little or no chance that Drumright coaches, players or their fans will see this but I thought it was worth saying and sharing! Setting up for the radio broadcast last night Drumright came out to warm up with only 12 kids in uniform! I was speaking with Jason Reed and Heath in the press box and almost at the exact same time we all said we have been there just a few seasons ago. I watched these 12 young men and their coaches go through their Friday night routine the game got out of hand score wise early these young men could have quit, could have started trying to hurt our players but they didnâ€™t! These young men fought hard and showed class till the end as did their coaches and fans! Following the game not only did Drumright players and coaches come back by for a second handshake coach Hennissey invited them to join the post game spirit ring once again showing the utmost class they joined hands and participated with the Huskies team and fans!!! Great sportmanship and class all around Drumright!!!

post_text:
Drumright Parents and Guardians,

Today at approximately 1:15p, we placed our campus on lockdown out of an abundance of caution.

One of our students notified the high school principal about a possible threat being made toward them through a fake social media account.
The Drumright Police Department is working with several law enforcement agencies to identify the person who used the fake account to make the threat.

We will be conducting a delayed release. Students will be escorted by law enforcement to their release point: parent/guardian car or their own car.
No students will be allowed to walk home. Parents will be called to pick up any students who walk, to come pick up their child.

Drumright Schools will continue to work with law enforcement and support the prosecution of anyone involved in making threats towards our students, staff or school. We will keep you posted as new information is provided to us.

We take your childrenâ€™s safety seriously and appreciate your support.
Sincerely,

Ashley Davis, Ed.D.
Superintendent

post_text:
Questions encourage your child to think about reading

You can help your child get more out of reading by asking questions about the story. First, ask basic questions like, "What was the story about?" Then help her move to a higher level of thinking by analyzing information in the story. You might ask, "Which character is most like you?" Finally, encourage your child to express opinions: "What do you think Goldilocks learned from going into the bears' house?"

post_text:
The writing on a word wall builds your child's vocabulary

Build your child's vocabulary by helping him make a "word wall." Here's how: Have your child find 10 new and interesting words in books he likes. He can then write each word on its own index card. Mount the cards on the wall in an easy-to-see place and help him make sentences with the words. When he's learned the first 10 words, have him make a new set of cards. Save the old cards for later review.

post_text:
Help your child focus on listening well

To succeed in school, children need good communication skills. One of them is listening. To build your child's skills, say her name to get her attention. Then look her in the eye and speak quietly; your child will have to listen closely. Model good listening by paying undivided attention when your child speaks to you. Encourage her to continue with statements like, "Tell me more."

http://niswc.com/15gDC129968

post_text:
Learning moments help your child stay off the 'summer slide'

The summer slide isn't a piece of playground equipment. It's the loss of skills that happens when kids don't practice what they've learned during the school year. Look for ways your child can use his skills this summer. You might ask him to keep a journal. Or have him estimate and measure water volume while he splashes in the pool or tub. Have him map the routes you travel and read road signs aloud.

post_text: Here are a few easy things you can do this summer to help your child become a strong reader. Start by keeping a variety of interesting reading materials throughout your home. When you read together, stop and ask questions about the story. Be sure to give your child time to answer, and show interest in her ideas. Ask her to retell stories to you, too. Have her say what she remembers and describe the pictures.
